"jsonContent":{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s19",
"title":{
"__html":"Secondary Amenorrhea"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"1ca3c2",
"children":[
"Secondary Amenorrhea"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s19_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e3b922",
"children":[
"Secondary amenorrhea is defined as absence of menses for more than 3 months in women who previously had regular menstrual cycles or 6 months in women who have irregular menses."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"5b2571",
"children":[
"History and physical examination include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f8b4ca",
"children":[
"history of obstetric complications, which could lead to endometrial damage, scarring, or adhesions"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"67d03c",
"children":[
"stress, weight loss, significant exercise, eating disorders"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a5547f",
"children":[
"newly initiated oral contraceptives, antipsychotics, or metoclopramide"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0650cb",
"children":[
"symptoms of pituitary adenoma (secondary to mass effect or hyperfunction)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"4415b9",
"children":[
"hirsutism, acne, history of ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"polycystic ovary syndrome",
"children":[
"PCOS"
]
}
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s19_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"976e28",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Test all women with secondary amenorrhea for pregnancy, the most common cause."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"50eec6",
"children":[
"In the absence of pregnancy, assess hormonal status with estradiol, ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"follicle-stimulating hormone",
"children":[
"FSH"
]
},
","
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"luteinizing hormone",
"children":[
"LH"
]
},
","
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"thyroid-stimulating hormone",
"children":[
"TSH"
]
},
","
]
},
" and prolactin levels."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d9c8f9",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Low estradiol"
]
},
" and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"low or inappropriately normal FSH and LH"
]
},
" indicate hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism. Causes include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"78c24e",
"children":[
"hypothyroidism"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a6d3b8",
"children":[
"hyperprolactinemia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9d13bb",
"children":[
"hypothalamic (stress, weight loss, exercise)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"279b94",
"children":[
"pituitary (tumor, Sheehan syndrome)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b8018f",
"children":[
"A progesterone challenge test is performed in these patients."
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ea8278",
"children":[
"No bleeding following a progesterone challenge indicates low estrogen because of hypothalamic hypogonadism; measure estradiol level to confirm."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a27b64",
"children":[
"Bleeding following progesterone challenge indicates a normal estrogen state and suggests possible hyperandrogenism (e.g., PCOS)."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b080b2",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Low estradiol"
]
},
" and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"elevated FSH and LH"
]
},
" levels indicate hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism. Consider:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9206e2",
"children":[
"premature ovarian insufficiency (autoimmune)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"03b879",
"children":[
"chemotherapy"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"bdc700",
"children":[
"pelvic radiation"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s19_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"293e0a",
"children":[
"Treat the underlying disorder. Prevent osteoporosis by choosing estrogen and progesterone replacement until menstruation returns to normal or age ~50 years. For hypothalamic amenorrhea, choose reduced exercise, improved nutrition, and attention to emotional needs."
]
}
]
}
]
},
